observations.recommendation:
a. maintain Property Cards (PCs) on all classes of PPE and henceforth prepare and maintain additional forms, registry, and reports for semi-expendable properties, as prescribed in COA Circular No. 2022-004, since issued semi-expendables are already derecognized in the books of accounts;
b. incorporate in the Report on the Physical Count of Semi-Expendable Property (RPCSP) the result of the physical count for the semi-expendables;
c. conduct a comprehensive physical count of Property, Plant and Equipment items of the Municipality following the inventory taking procedures and guidelines set forth or adopt COA Circular No. 2020-006 for the One-Time Cleansing of PPE Accounts, and subsequently submit to COA a complete RPCPPE, in the prescribed format, not later than January 31 of each year; and
d. coordinate with the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the accounting records with the result of actual physical count by the Inventory Committee to have a more reliable financial report.

a. recognize depreciation for the abovementioned asset accounts and effect the necessary adjusting entries;
b. expedite substantiation of recorded “unidentified” PPE items based on the result of the physical count, with the aid of other relevant corroborating documents, in accordance with the applicable guidelines;
c. reclassify the items costing less than ₱50,000.00 to semi-expendable property following the COA Circular No. 2022-004; and
d. henceforth, properly record the description of each item in the PPE schedule, indicating its individual/unit price and specify whether it is a set or not.
